# Interesting Facts About Octopuses

- Octopuses have **three hearts**: two pump blood to the gills, one pumps it to the rest of the body. The main heart actually *stops beating* when they swim, which is why they prefer crawling.

- They have **blue blood** — it uses copper-based hemocyanin instead of iron-based hemoglobin, which is more efficient at transporting oxygen in cold, low-oxygen deep-sea environments.

- Each of their **eight arms has its own mini-brain** (a cluster of neurons). About two-thirds of an octopus's neurons are in its arms, meaning each arm can taste, touch, and make decisions semi-independently.

- Octopuses can **change colour, pattern, and even skin texture** in milliseconds using specialised cells called chromatophores, iridophores, and papillae. They can mimic the appearance of rocks, coral, other animals, and even the sandy sea floor.

- The **mimic octopus** can impersonate at least 15 different species, including lionfish, flatfish, and sea snakes, choosing the best disguise for whatever predator is nearby.

- Octopuses are surprisingly **playful and curious** — they've been observed juggling hermit crabs, solving puzzles, unscrewing jar lids from the inside, and even squirting water at lab equipment they don't like.

- They have **excellent problem-solving abilities** and both short-term and long-term memory. They can learn by observation, which is rare among invertebrates.

- An octopus's **beak** (made of chitin) is the only hard part of its body. This means an octopus can squeeze through any opening larger than its beak — even a gap the size of a coin.

- Octopuses are **masters of camouflage** despite being colourblind. Scientists believe they may perceive colour through their skin, which contains light-sensitive proteins called opsins.

- The **blanket octopus** is immune to the stings of the Portuguese man-o-war and will rip off its tentacles to use as whip-like weapons against predators.